WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:19.600
Alright, so here we're going to talk about Beyond Static Reports with R Markdown.

00:00:19.600 --> 00:00:27.600
So hopefully everyone is somewhat familiar with R Markdown, but it's a file format that

00:00:27.600 --> 00:00:34.080
allows us to create HTML, PDF reports, Word documents.

00:00:34.080 --> 00:00:40.959
You can knit to presentations, but there's a whole world kind of beyond that of R Markdown

00:00:40.959 --> 00:00:46.520
and it's a really flexible format, allows us to do a lot of different things.

00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:51.439
So we're just going to walk through a couple of those different uses today.

00:00:51.439 --> 00:00:55.759
And with that, let's go ahead and jump right in.

00:00:56.160 --> 00:01:00.959
So hopefully everyone can see the IDE that I have pulled up here.

00:01:00.959 --> 00:01:06.800
This is kind of a classic R Markdown report, I'm going to call it a static report.

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:13.160
I'll go ahead and knit it so we can just know what we're talking about instead of just grinding

00:01:13.160 --> 00:01:14.879
through code.

00:01:14.879 --> 00:01:22.800
So this is going to create a report for Facebook, for FB, pulls in the price history of Facebook,

00:01:22.800 --> 00:01:24.760
it charts it.

00:01:24.760 --> 00:01:29.879
There's this really simple, what we're calling a forecast model down here in the bottom.

00:01:29.879 --> 00:01:33.559
And hopefully this looks really familiar to everyone as something you can accomplish with

00:01:33.559 --> 00:01:34.559
R Markdown.

00:01:34.559 --> 00:01:39.800
This is basically an HTML file, we could save this and send it to whoever we want and they

00:01:39.800 --> 00:01:44.120
would receive it and be able to read our work.

00:01:44.120 --> 00:01:50.800
The reason I think of this as being kind of the most static, almost even hard-coded, you

00:01:50.800 --> 00:01:57.639
can almost think of this as a hard-coded R Markdown file, is that everything is kind

00:01:57.639 --> 00:01:59.639
of explicitly defined here.

00:01:59.639 --> 00:02:06.639
This is a report that I'm saying is for FB, I'm passing in this ticker symbol, FB.

00:02:06.639 --> 00:02:11.679
There's a few more examples where it's just FB, FB, FB, that's really the guts of what's

00:02:11.679 --> 00:02:13.600
going on here.

00:02:13.600 --> 00:02:22.160
And that's great, but this is not really a document that's easily kind of changed or

00:02:22.160 --> 00:02:24.039
used for different purposes.

00:02:24.039 --> 00:02:29.320
So we can imagine if somebody said, wow, this report looks really great, could you set it

00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:34.520
up for Google, or for Amazon, or for Netflix, or some other stock?

00:02:34.520 --> 00:02:36.000
And we could definitely do that, right?

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:42.559
We could just do a control F and look for all the instances of FB and replace it with

00:02:42.559 --> 00:02:47.919
something like Goog, and we could say replace, replace, replace.

00:02:47.919 --> 00:02:50.520
That would work, right?

00:02:50.520 --> 00:02:57.080
It's probably a bad idea for a few reasons, one of which would be that this is a really

00:02:57.080 --> 00:03:02.800
simple report, though we would still almost inevitably make a mistake at some point.

00:03:02.800 --> 00:03:07.119
As you can see right here, I have Goog, and I'm actually pulling in data from Google,

00:03:07.119 --> 00:03:12.240
so if I did another find and replace on Goog, this immediately would mess me up.

00:03:12.919 --> 00:03:17.880
But even if we were really meticulous about that, you know, for one thing, we've lost

00:03:17.880 --> 00:03:22.080
our original report on Facebook, and so we could say, well, no problem, we'll just make

00:03:22.080 --> 00:03:26.600
a copy of this file, and we could call the first one Facebook report.RMD, and the next

00:03:26.600 --> 00:03:31.320
one Google.report.RMD, et cetera, et cetera.

00:03:31.320 --> 00:03:37.759
That would also work, but if we ever wanted to make any changes to maybe this forecast

00:03:37.800 --> 00:03:43.000
down here, maybe we want to make this maybe a little bit more complicated or a better

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:47.080
model instead of just calling this simple one, we would have to change it in every single

00:03:47.080 --> 00:03:49.639
one of those files.

00:03:49.639 --> 00:03:56.119
So our markdown has a more flexible way of doing this, and that's this concept of a parameterized

00:03:56.119 --> 00:03:57.119
report.

00:03:57.119 --> 00:04:03.720
Okay, so this file is going to produce basically the exact same report we were just looking

00:04:03.720 --> 00:04:06.360
at for Facebook.

00:04:06.360 --> 00:04:12.679
I'm just going to knit it here just so we can look at it and confirm that I'm not lying.

00:04:12.679 --> 00:04:15.479
So here's the exact same report.

00:04:15.479 --> 00:04:23.399
The difference is that up in the YAML, I created a parameter, and I named that parameter symbol

00:04:23.399 --> 00:04:28.200
because these are ticker symbols, and I gave it a default value of FB, right?

00:04:28.200 --> 00:04:34.160
So if we go back to our original document, you can see that the YAMLs look slightly different.

00:04:34.160 --> 00:04:38.440
But now if you search through this document, you won't see FB appearing anywhere else.

00:04:38.440 --> 00:04:42.640
You'll just see params dollar symbol.

00:04:42.640 --> 00:04:45.720
And here's params dollar symbol.

00:04:45.720 --> 00:04:53.059
So now if I want to create what we call a variant of this report for myself as the creator

00:04:53.059 --> 00:05:01.320
of this report, I don't have to do a control F and replace FB with goog everywhere.

00:05:01.320 --> 00:05:05.959
I could just do it right here, and I could say, great, okay, and I'm just going to pass

00:05:05.959 --> 00:05:08.200
in this ticker.

00:05:08.200 --> 00:05:11.239
So everywhere that originally there was FB, now there's this goog.

00:05:11.239 --> 00:05:12.839
This is one way you could do it.

00:05:12.839 --> 00:05:15.519
You could just change the default value.

00:05:15.519 --> 00:05:20.000
That's a perfectly valid way, and okay, it works.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:24.079
You could also, when you knit this, instead of just clicking on the knit, if you click

00:05:24.079 --> 00:05:28.359
on this downward arrow, you could say I want to knit it with parameters because what we've

00:05:28.359 --> 00:05:30.880
created here is a parameter.

00:05:30.880 --> 00:05:33.040
We've given it the name symbol, right?

00:05:33.040 --> 00:05:37.959
So maybe it looks a little familiar from the shiny world, and actually we get this little

00:05:37.959 --> 00:05:41.119
interface, and it's going to say, okay, well, what ticker do you want?

00:05:41.119 --> 00:05:47.480
Let's say I put in, I can put in Amazon, I could go back to FB, I could go away from

00:05:47.480 --> 00:05:51.119
the tech world and say, how about Goldman.

00:05:51.119 --> 00:05:59.079
But in any event, to me, this report has taken one step away from its original static,

00:05:59.079 --> 00:06:07.160
hard-coded nature, right, because it's a lot more flexible now for me to pop in different

00:06:07.160 --> 00:06:13.559
stock tickers, and indeed, any parameter that you wanted to pass into, say, this model,

00:06:13.559 --> 00:06:16.239
you could parameterize.

00:06:16.359 --> 00:06:22.000
So this is kind of the first step, right, towards, to me, making this a more dynamic

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:23.000
document.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:30.200
Again, I think two valuable things, one, less likely to make a mistake, two, now I can change

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:35.480
this underlying code without having to worry about doing it for all these different variants

00:06:35.480 --> 00:06:39.480
of this report.

00:06:39.480 --> 00:06:46.359
So I'm going to just kind of head on here, because that very simple case probably doesn't

00:06:46.359 --> 00:06:49.679
really jump out as being all that useful.

00:06:49.679 --> 00:06:51.399
So let's look at a slightly more complicated case.

00:06:51.399 --> 00:06:58.600
So here, I've almost intentionally created a lot of parameters that don't even fit on

00:06:58.600 --> 00:07:01.160
one screen.

00:07:01.160 --> 00:07:08.320
So this is a script that's going to take three stocks, these default values to Google, Amazon,

00:07:08.320 --> 00:07:13.559
Facebook, the parameters are stock one, stock two, stock three, each of them gets a weight.

00:07:13.559 --> 00:07:18.440
We're going to create a portfolio of stocks, so they need a weight in that portfolio.

00:07:18.440 --> 00:07:25.200
We're going to assign an interest rate, and we're going to have a starting date.

00:07:25.200 --> 00:07:31.559
And one of the things, so we're still up here in the YAML, and one of the things that this

00:07:31.559 --> 00:07:36.839
is going to show, I hope, is that the parameters don't just have to be text.

00:07:36.839 --> 00:07:42.600
They can be numeric, so the weights are all going to be numerics.

00:07:42.600 --> 00:07:49.160
This risk-free interest rate is going to be a slider input, this is going to be a date.

00:07:49.160 --> 00:07:53.160
Let's just knit this in its kind of default format.

00:07:53.160 --> 00:08:00.000
Hopefully it'll help show how we're moving towards things being a little bit more dynamic.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:06.760
And some of it depends on the point of view from which we're defining dynamic versus static.

00:08:07.279 --> 00:08:12.279
This point, to me, this document has become much more dynamic from our perspective as

00:08:12.279 --> 00:08:14.600
the creators of this document.

00:08:14.600 --> 00:08:18.359
From the end-user or the end-consumer's perspective, this is still static.

00:08:18.359 --> 00:08:24.920
They're still getting an HTML or a PDF report from us, right?

00:08:24.920 --> 00:08:26.239
From our perspective, it's more dynamic.

00:08:26.239 --> 00:08:29.079
We can change it faster.

00:08:29.079 --> 00:08:31.040
So here's what that document knits to.

00:08:31.040 --> 00:08:36.919
It's going to take our three stock tickers, combine them with the weightings that we gave

00:08:36.919 --> 00:08:37.919
them.

00:08:37.919 --> 00:08:40.159
It's going to tell us how a dollar would have grown.

00:08:40.159 --> 00:08:47.159
It calculates the Sharpe ratio, which measures the risk-reward trade-off of this portfolio.

00:08:47.159 --> 00:08:51.440
On page two here, it just shows us the monthly percentage returns of these individually,

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:55.280
if that's important to us.

00:08:55.280 --> 00:08:58.280
But there's a lot of parameters here, right?

00:08:59.280 --> 00:09:04.080
Hopefully this demonstrates a little bit more how, if we wanted to create a variant

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:08.559
of this, if this had been our original hard-coded example where we were going to go through

00:09:08.559 --> 00:09:15.119
and do a Control-F on every single parameter that we needed to change, that would get a

00:09:15.119 --> 00:09:21.159
little bit complicated here and we would become, I think, more likely to make an error, right?

00:09:21.159 --> 00:09:25.760
So we probably don't want to be doing a Control-F here and trying to change things throughout

00:09:25.760 --> 00:09:27.679
the code.

00:09:28.679 --> 00:09:34.719
And this also, I think, shows why it's going to get difficult to just change things directly

00:09:34.719 --> 00:09:35.719
in the YAML, right?

00:09:35.719 --> 00:09:38.239
Here it was easy to change the different tickers.

00:09:38.239 --> 00:09:42.119
There's only one, so we can pretty easily change the symbols.

00:09:42.119 --> 00:09:46.239
When we get to have more and more, we want to actually really make use of this knit with

00:09:46.239 --> 00:09:48.320
parameters button.

00:09:48.320 --> 00:09:51.520
So let's see what that looks like with these different formats.

00:09:51.520 --> 00:09:54.159
So one, we can change the title.

00:09:54.159 --> 00:10:05.760
How about Energy Stocks, BP, and Chevron, another one, Exxon.

00:10:05.760 --> 00:10:10.640
So these are all text inputs, as we had before, but now we have these numeric inputs, right?

00:10:10.640 --> 00:10:21.159
So we can change the weighting, so why don't we do a 40, 30, 30, sure.

00:10:21.159 --> 00:10:22.880
How about the risk-free rate we're assuming?

00:10:22.880 --> 00:10:28.280
We could take it up, that's going to make our Sharpe Ratio go down.

00:10:28.280 --> 00:10:33.880
The start date, 2013.

00:10:33.880 --> 00:10:42.239
So hopefully this is showing that this is, at least in my opinion, greatly decreasing

00:10:42.239 --> 00:10:46.440
the likelihood that we're going to make an error and miss one of these parameters somewhere.

00:10:47.280 --> 00:10:53.000
And it's making it a lot easier to kind of create variance in this report.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:56.640
And I'm going to walk through the code a little bit once we're done here, but I just wanted

00:10:56.640 --> 00:11:01.479
to show what the end result is going to look like, so that we're not just walking through

00:11:01.479 --> 00:11:02.760
code sort of blind.

00:11:02.760 --> 00:11:04.960
All right, so here's a new report, right?

00:11:04.960 --> 00:11:10.159
Growth of a dollar invested in energy has not been a great place to be for the last

00:11:10.159 --> 00:11:11.159
four years.

00:11:11.159 --> 00:11:16.320
So it actually has a negative Sharpe Ratio, but you can see that by changing all those

00:11:17.200 --> 00:11:20.599
parameters, we changed the title, now it's called Energy Stocks, right?

00:11:20.599 --> 00:11:22.080
Here's the individual returns.

00:11:22.080 --> 00:11:27.799
So it's pretty fast to iterate through different variants of reports for us as the archivators.

00:11:27.799 --> 00:11:33.440
Again, what the end user would be receiving here would still be quite static.

00:11:33.440 --> 00:11:39.760
So we'll just quickly look at how these parameters get passed down into the code.

00:11:39.760 --> 00:11:45.840
That portion of it is actually, you know, it's pretty, that part's pretty intuitive.

00:11:45.840 --> 00:11:48.640
You create your parameters up here, and then you pass them into the code the same way you

00:11:48.640 --> 00:11:50.799
would anything else, right?

00:11:50.799 --> 00:11:54.320
So this is just a function.

00:11:54.320 --> 00:11:57.820
It's not being affected at all by any of the parameters, right?

00:11:57.820 --> 00:12:02.760
So kind of the same as the way we loaded up an unparameterized report.

00:12:02.760 --> 00:12:09.159
Start with your packages and create whatever sort of function that you want.

00:12:09.159 --> 00:12:12.599
And then here's where we start passing in parameters, right?

00:12:12.599 --> 00:12:16.919
We have a portfolio name, that was one, that was our first parameter.

00:12:16.919 --> 00:12:19.640
Stock one is our second parameter.

00:12:19.640 --> 00:12:22.280
Started here with a date, parameter dollar date.

00:12:22.280 --> 00:12:27.880
So we're just passing in these parameters the same way as we would if we were, quote, unquote,

00:12:27.880 --> 00:12:30.080
hard coding them.

00:12:30.080 --> 00:12:34.239
But this just makes it a lot easier to create variants of this.

00:12:34.239 --> 00:12:38.799
So again, this is all sort of from the R coders perspective.

00:12:38.799 --> 00:12:45.080
This has become a more dynamic document and a lot easier to change.

00:12:45.080 --> 00:12:51.880
And if we did want to update this model in some way, you know, maybe we wanted to change

00:12:51.880 --> 00:12:58.119
this function to daily stock returns or weekly stock returns, you know.

00:12:58.119 --> 00:13:02.960
Or indeed, maybe if we wanted to have that be parameterized, you know, we can make this,

00:13:03.119 --> 00:13:09.280
we could add a parameter here, make this a text and call it something like, right, params

00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:12.200
dollar period or something like that, right?

00:13:12.200 --> 00:13:14.359
And then we could create a parameter up here.

00:13:14.359 --> 00:13:20.080
And then all of a sudden we'd be able to toggle between monthly, weekly, daily, different

00:13:20.080 --> 00:13:22.479
types of period returns.

00:13:22.479 --> 00:13:29.080
All right, so that's kind of another, at least to me, another nice thing about parameterizing

00:13:29.119 --> 00:13:34.280
these is that it's a little bit of a mindset shift because now all of a sudden this, to

00:13:34.280 --> 00:13:39.159
me anyway, this feels like a more dynamic document and I can start to think, well, what

00:13:39.159 --> 00:13:40.159
can I parameterize?

00:13:40.159 --> 00:13:41.719
What would be interesting to parameterize?

00:13:41.719 --> 00:13:45.960
Well, here, I think this period might be interesting to parameterize.

00:13:45.960 --> 00:13:46.960
We're getting log returns.

00:13:46.960 --> 00:13:48.719
We could parameterize that.

00:13:48.719 --> 00:13:54.760
Maybe we just want, if we don't want log returns for whatever reason, maybe we want continuous

00:13:54.760 --> 00:13:56.640
returns.

00:13:56.640 --> 00:14:02.159
The opposite side of that coin, of course, is you start to think about, well, what should

00:14:02.159 --> 00:14:05.280
I not be parameterizing, right?

00:14:05.280 --> 00:14:10.520
Maybe we want to enforce a risk-free rate, so maybe we might want to obliterate this

00:14:10.520 --> 00:14:14.840
and just quote unquote hard code the risk-free rate and say, this is one thing we're not

00:14:14.840 --> 00:14:15.840
going to toggle.

00:14:15.840 --> 00:14:16.840
It's an assumption.

00:14:16.840 --> 00:14:18.559
It's an unchanging assumption.

00:14:18.559 --> 00:14:22.799
Let's change everything else and see how the different reports come out.

00:14:22.799 --> 00:14:23.799
So a lot of flexibility.

00:14:23.799 --> 00:14:31.440
Again, this is for us as the creators of the reports.

00:14:31.440 --> 00:14:37.799
So to me, the ability to create these multiple parameters takes us another step towards being

00:14:37.799 --> 00:14:38.799
more dynamic.

00:14:38.799 --> 00:14:46.239
So this is the original hard-coded and then we just had one parameter and then we have

00:14:46.239 --> 00:14:47.239
a lot of parameters.

00:14:47.239 --> 00:14:51.059
I think this is maybe eight total parameters.

00:14:51.059 --> 00:14:52.059
We could keep going.

00:14:52.320 --> 00:14:55.539
If we go to 10, there's really no limit to the number of parameters that we can put in

00:14:55.539 --> 00:14:56.539
here.

00:14:56.539 --> 00:15:00.260
And then just, you know, we did it with parameters, it's going to give us a nice interface for

00:15:00.260 --> 00:15:01.260
changing them all.

00:15:01.260 --> 00:15:08.619
All right, so now, you know, hopefully I've convinced you that this parameterization is

00:15:08.619 --> 00:15:14.340
a valuable thing for us as the creators of these reports, but let's take the next step

00:15:14.340 --> 00:15:15.340
to Shiny.

00:15:15.340 --> 00:15:20.239
And this is where things are just, they're always going to be dynamic in the sense that

00:15:20.479 --> 00:15:25.479
even the end user is going to receive a dynamic document.

00:15:25.479 --> 00:15:30.039
And again, a lot of the important stuff is happening up here in the YAML, which to me

00:15:30.039 --> 00:15:35.960
is kind of the good news, even though as our coders, maybe the YAML isn't the most intuitive

00:15:35.960 --> 00:15:38.280
place for us to be.

00:15:38.280 --> 00:15:42.719
You know, it's nice that we can just make these changes up here and not have to touch

00:15:42.719 --> 00:15:44.200
our code a lot.

00:15:44.200 --> 00:15:48.719
There are some changes in the code, but this is really where a lot of the important changes

00:15:48.719 --> 00:15:50.479
in the format are happening.

00:15:50.479 --> 00:15:57.359
I'm just, again, going to quickly knit this, and then we're actually going to go way back

00:15:57.359 --> 00:16:02.640
to the beginning of Shiny apps, but I just want to show where we're headed with this

00:16:02.640 --> 00:16:06.559
Shiny world.

00:16:06.559 --> 00:16:16.239
So this is, you know, the most sort of dynamic iteration of this in the sense that here we'd

00:16:16.239 --> 00:16:20.200
be delivering this app to an end consumer.

00:16:20.200 --> 00:16:25.080
We'd be saying, you can choose your own stocks and your own weights, right?

00:16:25.080 --> 00:16:31.840
And you can see in real time how they change.

00:16:31.840 --> 00:16:35.239
So this is kind of inherently dynamic.

00:16:35.239 --> 00:16:38.960
It's never going to take a static state and just stay there.

00:16:38.960 --> 00:16:44.200
Both for us as the creators and for the end consumers, this is always going to be a dynamic

00:16:44.200 --> 00:16:45.200
document.

00:16:45.200 --> 00:16:48.039
So it looks very similar to those reports.

00:16:48.039 --> 00:16:51.520
I'm going to come back to the code here.

00:16:51.520 --> 00:16:55.760
I just wanted to quickly show where we're headed so that we can kind of get a picture

00:16:55.760 --> 00:16:57.760
of it.

00:16:57.760 --> 00:17:03.239
So this is the code that was used to create this.

00:17:03.239 --> 00:17:07.239
It's very similar to the code that was used to create those reports, but the main difference

00:17:07.239 --> 00:17:14.839
is up here in the YAML we have this runtime Shiny instead of having all these parameters.

00:17:15.479 --> 00:17:20.920
So when we include this runtime Shiny line, our machine, our local desktop where we're

00:17:20.920 --> 00:17:26.719
running this or whatever server this is sitting on knows, okay, this is a Shiny app.

00:17:26.719 --> 00:17:33.079
And when our machine sees these parameters, it knows, okay, this is a parameterized report

00:17:33.079 --> 00:17:38.000
or if we had this sitting on a Connect server somewhere, right?

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:44.339
But just in case there's maybe some people out there who are more familiar with the traditional

00:17:44.339 --> 00:17:48.699
way to create a Shiny app, I'm going to take a brief departure here and just start at the

00:17:48.699 --> 00:17:51.979
beginning with Shiny and then we'll come back to this and we'll go through the code.

00:17:51.979 --> 00:17:54.859
So we're just going to do a five-minute departure here.

00:17:54.859 --> 00:17:58.579
Okay, so here's kind of a classic Shiny app.

00:17:58.579 --> 00:18:01.099
It's sitting in an app.r file.

00:18:01.099 --> 00:18:05.660
This is the hello world example, right?

00:18:05.660 --> 00:18:09.939
One of the hello world examples where it can change the number of bins and see how it affects

00:18:09.939 --> 00:18:11.020
the histogram, right?

00:18:11.020 --> 00:18:17.579
So we have our inputs, a reactive sitting between these, and then our outputs, which

00:18:17.579 --> 00:18:19.859
is this histogram, right?

00:18:19.859 --> 00:18:22.859
So here it is in the app.r file.

00:18:22.859 --> 00:18:28.500
And then here's just a Flex Dashboard skeleton with runtime Shiny.

00:18:28.500 --> 00:18:34.180
So if you want to just get started and begin kind of playing around with Flex Dashboard

00:18:34.180 --> 00:18:39.500
and the ability to create Shiny apps there, what you can do is you can take your entire

00:18:39.500 --> 00:18:44.420
app.r file and you can copy it, right?

00:18:44.420 --> 00:18:46.660
So I just did Control-A, Control-C there.

00:18:46.660 --> 00:18:48.979
This is just if you want to get started playing around.

00:18:48.979 --> 00:18:56.300
And you can copy the entire app.r file into that first code chunk, right?

00:18:56.300 --> 00:18:58.819
Library Shiny UI fluid page.

00:18:58.819 --> 00:19:05.219
And you can run this document within the RMD and it will basically reproduce that Shiny

00:19:05.219 --> 00:19:07.660
app in a Flex Dashboard format.

00:19:07.819 --> 00:19:14.500
So I just copied the app.r over to Flex Dashboard and here's pretty much that exact same map,

00:19:14.500 --> 00:19:15.500
right?

00:19:15.500 --> 00:19:21.260
The reason I think it's useful to do this in the beginning, if you're just getting started

00:19:21.260 --> 00:19:27.099
and you're more used to app.r than using Flex Dashboard and R Markdown for creating Shiny

00:19:27.099 --> 00:19:33.339
apps, is you can kind of deconstruct the Shiny app and put it into its component pieces and

00:19:33.339 --> 00:19:37.500
see what is needed and what is not needed.

00:19:37.500 --> 00:19:46.060
In our Markdown-based Shiny app versus the more classic app.r Shiny app.

00:19:46.060 --> 00:19:50.780
So the first thing that's not needed is this Library Shiny.

00:19:50.780 --> 00:19:56.579
You can get rid of that because we've already called Runtime Shiny.

00:19:56.579 --> 00:19:58.219
So we don't need that.

00:19:58.219 --> 00:20:05.260
There's really no concept of UI and server in the Flex Dashboard in R Markdown.

00:20:05.260 --> 00:20:09.300
So we can get rid of that.

00:20:09.300 --> 00:20:14.540
You can see we had to do a lot of work here to tell the UI this is a sidebar layout.

00:20:14.540 --> 00:20:18.339
It's a sidebar panel, a fluid page title panel.

00:20:18.339 --> 00:20:27.339
That's not really how it's handled in our Markdown file.

00:20:27.339 --> 00:20:31.380
We just tell it up here, this is a sidebar.

00:20:32.060 --> 00:20:38.420
We drop in a line of dashes and that's how Flex Dashboard and R Markdown knows there's

00:20:38.420 --> 00:20:42.300
an element coming here and we told it that it's a sidebar.

00:20:42.300 --> 00:20:47.020
We can actually get rid of this fluid page.

00:20:47.020 --> 00:20:51.699
We can get rid of sidebar layout, sidebar panel, because I just told it it's a sidebar.

00:20:51.699 --> 00:20:56.780
To me this is going to be just a much simpler app.

00:20:56.780 --> 00:20:59.180
That's gone now.

00:21:00.180 --> 00:21:01.180
This is our sidebar.

00:21:01.180 --> 00:21:02.900
I've called it inputs.

00:21:02.900 --> 00:21:03.900
You can call it whatever you want.

00:21:03.900 --> 00:21:04.900
You can call it sidebar.

00:21:04.900 --> 00:21:08.380
You can really just give it any name you want.

00:21:08.380 --> 00:21:14.540
This is really what's telling R Markdown that this is a sidebar for inputs.

00:21:14.540 --> 00:21:17.140
I think we just want that slider there for inputs.

00:21:17.140 --> 00:21:22.739
We don't really want our outputs sitting in the sidebar.

00:21:22.739 --> 00:21:29.459
We're going to make that it's own code chunk and we'll come down here.

00:21:29.459 --> 00:21:32.260
We'll create a new code chunk for our outputs.

00:21:32.260 --> 00:21:42.060
We have all these extraneous parentheses, we can get rid of those.

00:21:42.060 --> 00:21:48.500
Main panel, we don't need that main panel and the reason why is that we've indicated

00:21:48.500 --> 00:21:51.099
here that this is a sidebar.

00:21:51.099 --> 00:21:58.540
We want to let R Markdown know that we're done with the sidebar by putting in another

00:21:58.540 --> 00:22:00.939
line of these dashes.

00:22:00.939 --> 00:22:04.819
Now R Markdown knows, okay, we're done with this sidebar.

00:22:04.819 --> 00:22:05.819
Let's go to the main panel.

00:22:05.819 --> 00:22:09.180
We don't need this anymore.

00:22:09.180 --> 00:22:13.219
We said there's no server or UI logic we have to deal with.

00:22:13.219 --> 00:22:17.300
Function input output, don't have to deal with that.

00:22:17.300 --> 00:22:19.979
Getting pretty close, I promise.

00:22:19.979 --> 00:22:22.660
Any app UI, well, we got rid of UI and server.

00:22:22.660 --> 00:22:25.579
We'll take this out.

00:22:25.579 --> 00:22:30.380
This is an orphan now, take care of that.

00:22:30.380 --> 00:22:31.380
Okay.

00:22:31.380 --> 00:22:35.739
Move this over just so it looks nicer.

00:22:35.739 --> 00:22:39.500
We have our inputs, we have our outputs.

00:22:39.500 --> 00:22:42.739
No UI, no server, logic really needed here.

00:22:42.739 --> 00:22:46.660
We can get rid of some of this white space, it doesn't really matter.

00:22:46.660 --> 00:22:48.900
Let's see what this looks like when we run it.

00:22:48.900 --> 00:22:53.180
It's an adventure to do these live.

00:22:53.180 --> 00:22:58.180
Never quite know what's going to happen when we deconstruct and reconstruct.

00:22:58.180 --> 00:23:04.300
This looks like a pretty close approximation of what we had before in our app.R file.

00:23:04.300 --> 00:23:12.780
It's probably a matter of personal preference or just aesthetics, which one we prefer.

00:23:12.780 --> 00:23:17.180
There's not really a big substantive difference between what you can do in app.R and what

00:23:17.260 --> 00:23:20.819
you can do in our markdown shiny file.

00:23:20.819 --> 00:23:24.420
I personally like this format better.

00:23:24.420 --> 00:23:26.300
I think this is simpler.

00:23:26.300 --> 00:23:31.380
I think that you could probably show this to someone who wasn't all that familiar with

00:23:31.380 --> 00:23:35.459
what we're doing here today and say, this is the sidebar.

00:23:35.459 --> 00:23:38.180
It has a slider input.

00:23:38.180 --> 00:23:40.260
These are where the outputs go.

00:23:40.260 --> 00:23:45.540
The output is going to be that histogram.

00:23:45.579 --> 00:23:51.219
To me, this is just a little bit more intuitive and a simpler way to lay out your shiny apps.

00:23:51.219 --> 00:23:56.180
There's nothing wrong, of course, with using the classic method of app.R, but today we're

00:23:56.180 --> 00:24:01.140
just talking about our markdown, so this is the way we're going with today.

00:24:01.140 --> 00:24:05.619
It is actually, you could make this even more parsimonious.

00:24:05.619 --> 00:24:06.619
You could take out this.

00:24:06.619 --> 00:24:10.619
You don't need plot output, output dollar displot.

00:24:10.619 --> 00:24:11.619
You could take that out.

00:24:11.619 --> 00:24:12.619
We could knit this.

00:24:12.619 --> 00:24:13.619
It would be fine.

00:24:14.619 --> 00:24:20.619
Just to prove I'm not lying, hopefully this is going to be fine.

00:24:20.619 --> 00:24:23.619
Okay, so it looks the exact same.

00:24:23.619 --> 00:24:25.819
I like to keep it in there, though.

00:24:25.819 --> 00:24:30.459
Again, this really is just a matter of preference.

00:24:30.459 --> 00:24:36.540
I just find mentally having this at the top makes it easier to just glance up and see

00:24:36.540 --> 00:24:39.219
that this is where I'm putting an output.

00:24:39.219 --> 00:24:43.579
It's not necessary to have it in there.

00:24:44.579 --> 00:24:51.060
Just to kind of complete this and show what I think is kind of the power of using R Markdown

00:24:51.060 --> 00:24:56.339
for creating shiny apps is, let's say we wanted to add another plot that was responsive to

00:24:56.339 --> 00:25:01.260
another slider, or really any input.

00:25:01.260 --> 00:25:09.739
It's really fast and easy to do that, R Markdown, so this is how you add a second slider.

00:25:09.739 --> 00:25:10.739
Just copy paste it.

00:25:10.900 --> 00:25:16.900
We're going to call it bins two to distinguish it from input bins one.

00:25:16.900 --> 00:25:26.180
I think we want another histogram that's going to be responsive to that one, and we want

00:25:26.180 --> 00:25:31.260
this to be responsive to bins two.

00:25:31.260 --> 00:25:38.739
We'll call this output two and this output two.

00:25:38.739 --> 00:25:45.780
Let's just knit this up.

00:25:45.780 --> 00:25:50.660
Now we have the histogram on the left is responsive to our first slider.

00:25:50.660 --> 00:25:53.540
Histogram on the right is responsive to our second slider.

00:25:53.540 --> 00:25:55.300
We could put these on different pages.

00:25:55.300 --> 00:25:56.900
We could reorient them.

00:25:56.900 --> 00:26:02.260
We could have a sidebar that just has the first slider, and then on the second page,

00:26:02.260 --> 00:26:05.660
a slider that just has the second one.

00:26:05.660 --> 00:26:12.819
The point, hopefully, that I'm demonstrating is it's really easy to add new elements and

00:26:12.819 --> 00:26:18.300
drop things into an R Markdown Flex Dashboard when you're building your shiny apps.

00:26:18.300 --> 00:26:23.800
For me, I just find it a little bit easier than dropping elements into the kind of classic

00:26:23.800 --> 00:26:31.420
app.r file where I would be dealing with these three calls if I wanted to put in a new input,

00:26:31.420 --> 00:26:35.180
and then I'd need to deal with my server logic.

00:26:35.180 --> 00:26:38.660
I just think it's a lot easier to kind of drop things in.

00:26:38.660 --> 00:26:45.020
There's a whole website devoted to Flex Dashboard called rmarkdown.rstudio.com slash Flex Dashboard,

00:26:45.020 --> 00:26:47.300
and then there's a whole section on Shiny.

00:26:47.300 --> 00:26:50.099
So I'm not going to go through this, but this is all out here.

00:26:50.099 --> 00:26:54.180
The different layouts are here.

00:26:54.180 --> 00:26:58.180
Some different examples of Shiny are here.

00:26:58.180 --> 00:27:03.500
So anyway, I highly encourage, if you want to get into building Shiny with R Markdown,

00:27:03.500 --> 00:27:05.900
this website's a good place.

00:27:05.900 --> 00:27:12.619
Okay, so that was a little bit of a detour just to make sure we're all on the same page

00:27:12.619 --> 00:27:21.300
in terms of how to port over Shiny apps that were constructed using the app.r format over

00:27:21.300 --> 00:27:22.300
to a Flex Dashboard.

00:27:23.020 --> 00:27:30.219
So now let's go back to the Flex Dashboard, the Shiny app we wanted to look at.

00:27:30.219 --> 00:27:36.619
It's basically going to be built on the exact same components as our example, right?

00:27:36.619 --> 00:27:37.900
So here's our example.

00:27:37.900 --> 00:27:40.579
The key line here is runtime Shiny.

00:27:40.579 --> 00:27:41.579
Same here, runtime Shiny.

00:27:41.579 --> 00:27:48.579
We're going to load up our packages here in the setup chunk, and we're going to define

00:27:48.579 --> 00:27:51.300
our functions.

00:27:51.300 --> 00:27:55.459
So very similar to any other Shiny app.

00:27:55.459 --> 00:27:58.819
You can define whatever functions you want up here in the setup, and then they're accessible

00:27:58.819 --> 00:27:59.819
to you.

00:27:59.819 --> 00:28:05.540
A question that we get a lot about Shiny in general is, well, what functions can I drop

00:28:05.540 --> 00:28:06.540
into a Shiny app?

00:28:06.540 --> 00:28:08.140
The answer is any of them.

00:28:08.140 --> 00:28:13.579
Any function you can create here can be called in this app.

00:28:13.579 --> 00:28:19.900
So then, just to kind of refresh everyone what this app looked like, because I know

00:28:19.900 --> 00:28:25.939
we took a detour over there to look at the Hello World example.

00:28:25.939 --> 00:28:29.060
We have this sidebar in our Hello World example.

00:28:29.060 --> 00:28:31.219
This was just the slider input.

00:28:31.219 --> 00:28:37.739
But here we have the stocks, their weights, starting date, the risk-free rate.

00:28:37.739 --> 00:28:48.459
This is sitting in our sidebar, and the actual chart is sitting over here in our row.

00:28:48.459 --> 00:28:49.660
So that's happening right here.

00:28:50.420 --> 00:28:54.140
That's our sidebar.

00:28:54.140 --> 00:28:59.099
The reason this is double-line instead of single-line is that you'll notice when we

00:28:59.099 --> 00:29:03.339
toggle back to it that this sidebar only appears on the first page of this app.

00:29:03.339 --> 00:29:07.819
It doesn't appear on the second page.

00:29:07.819 --> 00:29:13.939
So here's how we constructed the sidebar for this Shiny app.

00:29:13.939 --> 00:29:19.020
And I actually did use the fluid row format here, and there's a reason for that, which

00:29:19.020 --> 00:29:28.660
is that this Shiny app is trying to put a lot of elements into this sidebar.

00:29:28.660 --> 00:29:30.099
So we have eight inputs.

00:29:30.099 --> 00:29:33.180
If we didn't go with that fluid row, they would just be stacked.

00:29:33.180 --> 00:29:39.099
So we would have eight different boxes, one, two, three, and it would start to get, I think,

00:29:39.099 --> 00:29:41.900
kind of hard to see it on one screen.

00:29:41.900 --> 00:29:46.060
So the reason that I went with that fluid row is just to be able to put them next to

00:29:46.060 --> 00:29:47.060
each other.

00:29:47.099 --> 00:29:50.579
So it's a little bit more intuitive to have the weights there.

00:29:50.579 --> 00:29:59.500
So the point is that you're not going to lose the ability to put nuanced layouts into your

00:29:59.500 --> 00:30:01.859
Shiny app by going with our markdown.

00:30:01.859 --> 00:30:09.060
The same things that were available to us in app.ar are available to us within the sidebar.

00:30:09.060 --> 00:30:14.420
I still think it's a little bit easier just to house them within this sidebar call.

00:30:14.420 --> 00:30:22.540
So we have our reactive inputs, stock one, weight one.

00:30:22.540 --> 00:30:29.099
Basically we're mirroring the parameters that we had here in our parameterized report.

00:30:29.099 --> 00:30:33.819
Stock two, weight two, and I'll stop toggling in a second because I'm sure everyone kind

00:30:33.819 --> 00:30:34.819
of gets it.

00:30:34.819 --> 00:30:37.780
Stock two, weight two.

00:30:37.780 --> 00:30:39.219
The code is very similar.

00:30:39.219 --> 00:30:43.140
It has a different layout because in this case we want the user to have the chance to

00:30:43.140 --> 00:30:46.699
actually do it themselves.

00:30:46.699 --> 00:30:53.540
And then we come down to where we're actually going to be passing those reactive inputs

00:30:53.540 --> 00:30:59.420
to the function that we defined up in the setup code chunk.

00:30:59.420 --> 00:31:11.060
So we pass in the year, stock one, stock two, stock three, and we calculate portfolio growth.

00:31:11.060 --> 00:31:16.739
We're going to calculate the sharp ratio, which is what's sitting in those value boxes.

00:31:16.739 --> 00:31:17.739
These are all just calculations.

00:31:17.739 --> 00:31:23.459
We haven't actually done any charting and graphing yet.

00:31:23.459 --> 00:31:26.540
This is an interesting place to look at a Shiny app.

00:31:26.540 --> 00:31:30.579
So here's three lines that are layout oriented.

00:31:30.579 --> 00:31:33.380
They're not substantive.

00:31:33.380 --> 00:31:38.819
With these double lines, we're telling this Shiny app, this is page one.

00:31:38.819 --> 00:31:44.260
And we're saying this is the first row of page one, and this is the name of it.

00:31:44.260 --> 00:31:49.060
So remember that portfolio growth, row, group of $1, maybe we want to call it something

00:31:49.060 --> 00:31:54.380
like portfolio performance.

00:31:54.380 --> 00:32:04.339
Let's see how that affected the end result of the app.

00:32:04.339 --> 00:32:06.900
So now this is page one, portfolio performance.

00:32:06.979 --> 00:32:11.380
When we toggle to page two, you're going to notice this sidebar is going to go away.

00:32:11.380 --> 00:32:13.380
Or no, actually, I'm sorry.

00:32:13.380 --> 00:32:18.099
The reason the sidebar doesn't go away is that we defined it as a universal sidebar.

00:32:18.099 --> 00:32:23.140
If you come back up here to the top, you'll see these double lines are telling this app,

00:32:23.140 --> 00:32:26.420
this sidebar is universal.

00:32:26.420 --> 00:32:31.300
Normally this is how you define a page, but since we called sidebar first, Flex Dashboard

00:32:31.300 --> 00:32:37.060
and R Markdown know, okay, we're calling a universal sidebar that we can keep toggling

00:32:37.060 --> 00:32:40.020
no matter what page we go to.

00:32:40.020 --> 00:32:42.219
So that's kind of a substantive choice.

00:32:42.219 --> 00:32:48.380
Do we want each page to give the user the ability to change inputs and outputs?

00:32:48.380 --> 00:32:52.500
Sometimes yes, sometimes no, sometimes we won't want that.

00:32:52.500 --> 00:32:54.979
So back to page one, which was portfolio performance.

00:32:54.979 --> 00:32:58.219
We said this is going to be our first row, we're going to call it growth of $1.

00:32:58.219 --> 00:33:05.339
And then very similar to what we did in our hello world example, we have, in this case,

00:33:05.339 --> 00:33:06.900
it's a DY graph output.

00:33:06.900 --> 00:33:13.219
In our hello world example, we just called it plot output because that's in base R.

00:33:13.219 --> 00:33:17.540
We're using a simple plot of the histogram.

00:33:17.540 --> 00:33:26.819
Here we're using DY graph, so we're going to call DY graph output, $graph, render DY

00:33:27.020 --> 00:33:30.540
graph, and we're going to pass in our reactive to it here.

00:33:30.540 --> 00:33:37.699
So very similar to actually our hello world example, the only difference here is we have

00:33:37.699 --> 00:33:45.180
a couple of functions, more complicated functions, sitting in between our inputs and our outputs.

00:33:45.180 --> 00:33:50.619
That's really the only difference is that instead of just passing in these tickers straight

00:33:50.619 --> 00:33:56.619
to our output, we're running them through these functions here.

00:33:56.619 --> 00:34:02.979
Other than that, this is really just the exact same as this hello world example.

00:34:02.979 --> 00:34:09.500
So hopefully I'm convincing you that you can take your app.R, shiny apps, and kind of parse

00:34:09.500 --> 00:34:15.580
them into an R Markdown file and have them do the same thing in what I think is a nice

00:34:15.580 --> 00:34:16.580
format.

00:34:16.580 --> 00:34:20.300
And then let's take one more look at this app.

00:34:20.300 --> 00:34:22.439
We're not just looking at code.

00:34:22.439 --> 00:34:29.199
You might have noticed that in addition to the chart that's showing the growth of $, which

00:34:29.199 --> 00:34:39.639
is here, which is here, we also have these two value boxes down here, and those are going

00:34:39.639 --> 00:34:45.320
to be responsive to any change that we make to the calculating chart ratio.

00:34:45.320 --> 00:34:50.959
So let's look at the Flex Dashboard code and how we actually put this into the file.

00:34:51.479 --> 00:34:56.520
Well, we had to tell our Markdown there's a new row coming, because the first row had

00:34:56.520 --> 00:35:00.320
that chart that was showing the growth of $, so we had to tell it, okay, there's a new

00:35:00.320 --> 00:35:08.679
row, and the first piece of that row is going to be called the sharp ratio of our portfolio,

00:35:08.679 --> 00:35:12.520
and it's a value box.

00:35:12.520 --> 00:35:18.239
And it's going to, again, depend on that reactive sharp ratio that we defined up above, which

00:35:18.239 --> 00:35:21.360
again is really just the inputs passed through some functions.

00:35:21.360 --> 00:35:27.000
So we said, okay, new row, first value box is here, and then with these three hashes,

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:28.080
we said there's a second.

00:35:28.080 --> 00:35:33.000
There's a second element coming, and that second element is also going to be a value

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:34.000
box.

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:41.360
Okay, so that's how we told our Markdown that there's a new row, it's going to be these

00:35:41.360 --> 00:35:45.320
value boxes, and we don't want them to be very high, because we're just showing a couple

00:35:45.320 --> 00:35:46.320
of numbers.

00:35:46.919 --> 00:35:53.840
We said data height 200, which is really just an aesthetic that we're setting, and it's

00:35:53.840 --> 00:36:00.239
a relative aesthetic in the sense that it's not an absolute 200.

00:36:00.239 --> 00:36:05.600
It's going to say, well, if this is 600, and down below is 200, it's going to set these

00:36:05.600 --> 00:36:10.760
heights relatively, which is why down here we said, okay, let's make this data height

00:36:10.760 --> 00:36:11.760
350.

00:36:11.760 --> 00:36:14.560
This is just some background on the sharp ratio.

00:36:15.560 --> 00:36:19.239
It's really just here to kind of show that you can also include static content.

00:36:19.239 --> 00:36:22.000
Not everything has to be reactive.

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:27.919
When you're building a Shiny app in our Markdown, you can still put in, just like you always

00:36:27.919 --> 00:36:30.959
can in our Markdown, you can still put in your text, right?

00:36:30.959 --> 00:36:34.800
So if you want to have some text in here, and you want to write something up about your

00:36:34.800 --> 00:36:40.679
Shiny app, you can still drop that in to your Shiny application, right?

00:36:40.679 --> 00:36:45.320
