same.

00:42:44.379 --> 00:42:47.820
We start out by loading up these packages, right?

00:42:47.820 --> 00:42:50.020
This is all three files.

00:42:50.020 --> 00:42:56.260
And then, second thing we do in each of them is we load up this .R file.

00:42:56.260 --> 00:43:04.340
And that .R file has a set of functions that I defined earlier.

00:43:04.340 --> 00:43:11.780
One to calculate component returns, which is here, it's the first one, right?

00:43:11.780 --> 00:43:19.020
The second function in here calculates contribution to volatility of each asset that's chosen.

00:43:19.020 --> 00:43:23.379
And then, the last one calculates the portfolio volatility, right?

00:43:23.379 --> 00:43:26.060
Doesn't matter what the substance is.

00:43:26.060 --> 00:43:32.540
The point is that one of the things that I think makes building Shiny apps in R Markdown

00:43:32.540 --> 00:43:37.820
quite efficient is that if you're building a report using R Markdown, and you're building

00:43:37.820 --> 00:43:41.739
a parameterized report using R Markdown, and then you're building a Shiny app using R Markdown,

00:43:42.699 --> 00:43:47.820
they can all use the same helpers function, right?

00:43:47.820 --> 00:43:53.739
So to me, that's nice because I don't have to worry about changing all three of these, right?

00:43:53.739 --> 00:44:00.219
If I want to mess around or test out functions over here, I can just do it in this one file

00:44:00.219 --> 00:44:04.100
and then all three of these are pulling them in, right?

00:44:04.100 --> 00:44:05.860
Kind of same with formatting.

00:44:05.860 --> 00:44:12.419
There's a lot of efficiencies to be gained if you spend a lot of time formatting a report

00:44:12.419 --> 00:44:13.419
the way you want it.

00:44:13.419 --> 00:44:17.540
So this is our unparameterized report.

00:44:17.540 --> 00:44:20.979
If you spend time kind of formatting this and getting it to look and feel the way you

00:44:20.979 --> 00:44:27.100
want, and then you decide, I want to turn this into a Shiny app, it's not a lot of work

00:44:27.100 --> 00:44:30.659
to take this structure and put it over here.

00:44:30.659 --> 00:44:34.860
In fact, it's going to be really, really similar.

00:44:34.860 --> 00:44:40.699
Once you have the look and feel the way you want it and your unparameterized static report,

00:44:40.699 --> 00:44:44.979
you can take it to a parameterized and a less static report, and then you can take it to

00:44:44.979 --> 00:44:52.020
Shiny and all the trial and error that went into making this report look good, almost

00:44:52.020 --> 00:44:54.939
all of that learning is going to translate into your Shiny app.

00:44:54.939 --> 00:45:00.540
It's going to be a little bit different because the look and feel will vary because in the

00:45:00.540 --> 00:45:05.580
Shiny app, of course, you're giving the user that sidebar inputs where they can actually

00:45:05.580 --> 00:45:11.379
put stuff, change stuff, so you need to kind of think about that, but other than that,

00:45:11.379 --> 00:45:14.139
these formats are going to mirror each other.

00:45:14.139 --> 00:45:19.659
So I kind of find that there's a lot of efficiencies, especially for someone like myself.

00:45:19.659 --> 00:45:24.179
I don't really want to spend a lot of time thinking about formatting.

00:45:24.179 --> 00:45:26.540
I want to spend as little time there as possible.

