timing that's having to do that for three different stocks.

00:46:53.020 --> 00:47:00.939
So I'll push go here, and you'll see it's going to take a second to run, and I'm kind

00:47:00.939 --> 00:47:02.939
of doing that on purpose.

00:47:02.939 --> 00:47:16.659
All right, so you can see that this app didn't start running until I pushed go, which is

00:47:16.659 --> 00:47:22.100
different from this app, from the Sharpe Ratio app.

00:47:22.100 --> 00:47:26.139
This was calculating the new Sharpe Ratio every time we changed a parameter, which really

00:47:26.139 --> 00:47:28.340
isn't that efficient.

00:47:28.340 --> 00:47:32.899
It isn't that big of a deal if your app is going to run extremely quickly, meaning it

00:47:32.899 --> 00:47:35.500
isn't doing a lot of heavy computations.

00:47:35.500 --> 00:47:42.300
But for this volatility app, I don't really want that, because every single time anything

00:47:42.300 --> 00:47:46.300
here gets changed, if I didn't have this go button, it would start trying to recalculate,

00:47:46.300 --> 00:47:52.699
recalculate, recalculate, and that would eventually drive our end users insane.

00:47:52.699 --> 00:47:58.659
So apologies if this is kind of old hat for people, but the way that we handled that was

00:47:58.659 --> 00:48:02.979
here with this action button go.

00:48:02.979 --> 00:48:08.659
So clearly what that's doing is it's waiting for someone to push go before anything happens,

00:48:08.659 --> 00:48:13.939
and then the link between this button and the rest of our app is right here.

00:48:13.939 --> 00:48:20.939
So instead of creating a straight up reactive, which is what we were doing here in our original

00:48:20.939 --> 00:48:27.100
app, our Sharpe Ratio app, these are just reactives.

00:48:27.100 --> 00:48:30.459
They're not waiting for anything, they're just waiting for inputs.

00:48:30.459 --> 00:48:32.979
Reactive, reactive, reactive.

00:48:32.979 --> 00:48:41.100
Here we're using an event reactive, and this event reactive is saying wait for input $go,

00:48:41.100 --> 00:48:44.540
and don't do anything until you get that input $go.

00:48:44.540 --> 00:48:49.419
So I just, it's not specific at all to our Markdown Shiny apps.

00:48:49.419 --> 00:48:56.419
This is the same as you would have in a normal app.r, but I like to just kind of point it

00:48:56.419 --> 00:49:02.300
out whenever I'm going through Shiny apps because it can save your end users a lot of

00:49:02.300 --> 00:49:08.459
grief and frustration from having things run every single time they change an input.

00:49:08.459 --> 00:49:13.260
And it's really, it's not hard to get this set up.

00:49:13.260 --> 00:49:21.899
You just add an action button, it doesn't have to say go, it can say submit or something.

00:49:21.899 --> 00:49:25.659
Whatever you kind of want to tell people to do.

00:49:25.659 --> 00:49:29.320
It's just waiting for input go to get fired off.

00:49:29.320 --> 00:49:34.300
So that's going to, it's not really going to change the performance of your app, and

00:49:34.300 --> 00:49:37.020
since we're doing two calculations, we need it twice here.

00:49:37.020 --> 00:49:39.340
So I'm calling two reactives input $go.

00:49:39.580 --> 00:49:46.060
This probably isn't the greatest construction in the world, but what it's saying is, so

00:49:46.060 --> 00:49:53.580
now Render Highchart knows, Render Highchart is waiting to get this value, portfolio rolling

00:49:53.580 --> 00:49:54.580
standard deviation.

00:49:54.580 --> 00:49:58.899
So it's waiting for that input $go to get fired off, because then that's when these

00:49:58.899 --> 00:50:01.699
values are going to get passed down to it.

00:50:01.699 --> 00:50:07.540
So that's just going to make life a little bit easier on your end users.

